The first step of NRT VI calculation is to mosaic the daily MODIS images and clip the area to the CONUS. Then the NDVI is calculated using surface reflectance bands of the MODIS data, which is defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)=\frac{NI{R}_{i}\left(x,y\right)-Re{d}_{i}\left(x,y\right)}{NI{R}_{i}\left(x,y\right)+Re{d}_{i}\left(x,y\right)}$$\end{document}NDVIix,y=NIRix,y−Redix,yNIRix,y+Redix,ywhere NIRi and Redi represent the surface reflectance value for the near-infrared band and red band of each pixel. Based on the above equation, the NDVI value ranges from −1 to 1. The common NDVI value range for vegetation is 0.2 to 0.821. The weekly and biweekly NDVI data are calculated by picking up the maximum daily raw NDVI in the 7-day/14-day period for every week/two-week using the maximum value composite (MVC) method. This is different from the rolling 8-day average method used in MODIS VI products (MOD13Q4N/MOD13A4N). The MVC method will keep the pixel of the maximum value from daily NDVI maps within a week or two weeks. This method can efficiently reduce the effect of bad pixels (e.g., cloud, fog, or no data) in a single daily NDVI.

To reduce the file size, we converted the NDVI data type from float to integer by scaling the index range from [−1, 1] to [0, 250], which can be defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$NDV{I}_{scaled}(x,y)=NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)\times 125+125$$\end{document}NDVIscaled(x,y)=NDVIix,y×125+125

VCI is a vegetation index derived from historical NDVI22. It indicates the percentage of the difference between the current NDVI value and historical minimum NDVI value with the NDVI dynamic range, which is defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$VC{I}_{i}(x,y)=\frac{NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)-NDV{I}_{min}\left(x,y\right)}{NDV{I}_{max}\left(x,y\right)-NDV{I}_{min}\left(x,y\right)}$$\end{document}VCIi(x,y)=NDVIix,y−NDVIminx,yNDVImaxx,y−NDVIminx,ywhere NDVIi(x,y) represents the current NDVI value for the given pixel, NDVImax(x, y) and NDVImin(x, y) represent the maximum and minimum value of the historical NDVI time series for the given pixel.

Similar to NDVI data, the index range of VCI is rescaled from [0, 1] to [0, 250], which can be defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$VC{I}_{scaled}(x,y)=VC{I}_{i}(x,y)\times 250$$\end{document}VCIscaled(x,y)=VCIi(x,y)×250

MVCI and RMVCI are indices measuring the deviation of the current year’s NDVI value to the mean and median value of the historical NDVI from 2000 to the current year. The equations of MVCI and RMVCI are respectively defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$MVC{I}_{i}(x,y)=\frac{NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)-NDV{I}_{mean}\left(x,y\right)}{NDV{I}_{mean}\left(x,y\right)}$$\end{document}MVCIi(x,y)=NDVIix,y−NDVImeanx,yNDVImeanx,y\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$RMVC{I}_{i}(x,y)=\frac{NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)-NDV{I}_{median}\left(x,y\right)}{NDV{I}_{median}\left(x,y\right)}$$\end{document}RMVCIi(x,y)=NDVIix,y−NDVImedianx,yNDVImedianx,ywhere NDVIi
(x,y) represents the current NDVI value for the given pixel. NDVImean
(x,y) and NDVImedian
(x,y) represent the mean and median value of the historical NDVI within the same period for the given pixel.

RVCI, on the other hand, stands for the ratio of the current year’s NDVI to the previous years within the same periods. The equation is listed as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$RVC{I}_{i}(x,y)=\frac{NDV{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)-NDV{I}_{i-1}\left(x,y\right)}{NDV{I}_{i-1}\left(x,y\right)}$$\end{document}RVCIi(x,y)=NDVIix,y−NDVIi−1x,yNDVIi−1x,ywhere NDVIi
(x, y) represents the NDVI value of the current year and NDVIi-1
(x, y) represents the NDVI value of the previous year.

To reduce the file size and remove the anomaly pixels, we limited the absolute value of the ratio to 125% and scaled the index range to [0, 250]. This conversion can be defined as:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V{I}_{scaled}(x,y)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}0 & if\;V{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)\le -1.25\\ V{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)\times 100+125 & if-1.25 < V{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right) < 1.25\\ 250 & if\;V{I}_{i}\left(x,y\right)\ge 1.25\end{array}\right.$$\end{document}VIscaled(x,y)=0ifVIix,y≤−1.25VIix,y×100+125if−1.25<VIix,y<1.25250ifVIix,y≥1.25
